Longest Common Prefix
Learning Sources

LeetCode: https://leetcode.com/problems/longest-common-prefix/

Problem Statement

Write a function to find the longest common prefix string among an array of strings.

If there is no common prefix, return an empty string "".

Example
Input
["flower","flow","flight"]
Output
"fl"
Explanation

All strings start with "fl".

At index 2:

flower → o
flow   → o
flight → i

Mismatch occurs, so the longest common prefix is "fl".

Another Example
Input
["dog","racecar","car"]
Output
""
Explanation

The first characters are different.

dog      → d
racecar  → r
car      → c

No common prefix exists.

Concept Used
String Traversal
Character Comparison
Nested Loops
Prefix Matching
My Understanding

To find the longest common prefix:

Take the first string as a reference.

Check each character of the first string with the character at the same index in all other strings.

If any character is different or a string ends, stop and return the prefix found so far.

If all characters match, the entire first string is the common prefix.

My Approach
Take the first string as reference.
Traverse each character of the first string.
Compare it with the same index in every other string.
If mismatch occurs, return prefix till that index.
If loop completes, return the first string.
Algorithm
Start from index 0.
Take current character from first string.
Compare with all other strings.
If:
character is different OR
index exceeds string length
return prefix till current index.
Otherwise continue.
Return first string if all characters match.
Code in Java
class Solution {

    public String longestCommonPrefix(String[] strs) {

        if (strs == null || strs.length == 0)
            return "";

        for (int i = 0; i < strs[0].length(); i++) {

            char ch = strs[0].charAt(i);

            for (int j = 1; j < strs.length; j++) {

                if (i >= strs[j].length() ||
                    strs[j].charAt(i) != ch) {

                    return strs[0].substring(0, i);
                }
            }
        }

        return strs[0];
    }
}
